                  <div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				Which is why I stipulated all other things being equal. And chances of two people being put on the list at exactly the same time are too high to make the issue a point. Chances of two candidates being exactly equal are as well, imo. I don't think that kind of problem is one that requires worrying about. In any event, I'm definitely not going to say that just because someone is younger, they are more deserving. 
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>
Exactly - the chances of all things being equal are just as high as the chance that they both wind up on the list at the exact same time (actually i think the latter is more likely due to the way administrative tasks like this are usually handled, but i'll agree for the sake of argument).  But 'first come first served 'is not really the best policy for organs imo and am i reasonably sure that is not the policy that is used.  At some point, someone has to make the unsavory decision of who is a better candidate - which is not necessarily who is more deserving, but rather who would be most likely to get the best benefit from the transplant and the least likely to 'waste' it by not having many years left to them in the first place, or due to lifestyle choices, etc.  Someone has to make these decisions and they can't just throw up their hands and evade the hard questions.  Triage is a medical necessity.  It's easy to say something simple and heartfelt like the statement i was initially responding to - that there should be no moral consideration involved when deciding who lives and who dies, but at our current level of technology that is simply not possible.
                  
		</div>
